FSVC3 (FreeBBN Standard Video Container v3)

"If it has a screen, Bad Apple will be seen."

FSVC3 is an ultra-lightweight, zero-bloat multimedia container format designed natively for the FreeBBN project (a modern, open-source recreation of the PlayStation Broadband Navigator for the PS2).

Instead of exhausting valuable retro CPU cycles or memory buffers on heavy modern prediction math or complex MPEG parsing, FSVC3 treats video and audio compilation as a strict, high-speed binary state machine language. The encoder handles the heavy work, allowing the C player core to remain minimal, fast, and light enough to run smoothly on legacy hardware.
Architectural Breakdown & Core Optimizations

The container utilizes a set of 1-byte instruction tags (Opcodes) to parse stream bytes on a rolling loop:

    Coordinate Target Delta Compression Engine (0xF1 / 0xF2): Rather than continuously re-dumping identical pixel clusters, the encoder maps frame-by-frame shifts. It evaluates color structures and only streams specific 7-byte absolute position records (X, Y, R, G, B) for pixels that actually changed color state.

    Hardware-Locked AV Sync (0xF3 / 0xF4): Constant-time 1102-byte raw PCM audio packets are strictly interleaved directly ahead of their matching video payloads, guaranteeing uniform streaming and hardware-locked synchronization.

Opcode Specification Map
0xF0 -> OP_DATA_START   (strictly at 0x40)
0xF1 -> OP_FRAME_START  (Indicates incoming video frame data)
0xF2 -> OP_FRAME_END    (Flushes frame buffer state to physical display hardware)
0xF3 -> OP_AUDIO_START  (Indicates incoming synchronized raw PCM block)
0xF4 -> OP_AUDIO_END    (Closes audio processing segment)
0xFF -> OP_DATA_END     (end of data, also end of file)

