0x00-0x04 fsvc3 signature
0x05-0x06 Width as Binary encoded decimal (max 9999)
0x07-0x08 Height as Binary encoded decimal (max 9999)
0x09-0x0C Amount of frames in the file (reversed!) (1E 11 00 00 = 00 00 11 1E = 4382 frames!!!)
0x0D Frame-to-Frame delay (50ms = 20FPS)
0x0E-0x0F padding
0x10-0x40 Optional metadata, can be left as 00
0x40-EOF actual data, the bit 0x40 has to be F0 STRICTLY


Getting Started & Repository Structure

To run the pipeline and witness the compilation and real-time player decoding loop, make sure your working folder contains:

    convert.py (The Python asset packaging compiler script)

    player.c (The ANSI C standard runtime decoder environment)

    video.mp4 (Your targeted demo video file—e.g., Bad Apple!!)

1. Compile the Source Code

Ensure you have a standard C compiler (like gcc) available on your system environment:
Bash

gcc player.c -o player -lSDL2

2. Encode the Media File

Run the Python script to let the compression engine ingest your media file assets, evaluate deltas, optimize block changes, and pack them into our binary file output layout format:
Bash

python3 encoder.py

This will automatically generate your optimized video.fsvc3 binary package footprint.
3. Launch the Playback Loop

Execute the newly built player binary, and see the rendering in real-time:
Bash

./player

